        text: 'Tatra śrīr vijayo bhūtir dhruvā nītiḥ — there abide prosperity, victory, power, and righteousness. The Advaita reading sees the final verse as pointing to the inner landscape: wherever the Self (represented by Krishna, the yogeśvara) is recognized and the discriminative wisdom (represented by Arjuna, the archer whose bow of discernment is raised) is fully active, there the fruits of self-realisation naturally manifest. Victory is the victory over ignorance. Prosperity is the inexhaustible richness of the Self. Power is the effortless sovereignty of the one who lives from the ground of being. Righteousness is the natural dharma of the one who acts from truth. These are not rewards granted from outside — they are the inner qualities that flower when the Self is known.',
